# Named Types Over Inline Object Types

Always define a named `interface` or `type` for object shapes, even when used only locally in one file. Never use inline `{ key: type }` as a return type or parameter type.

```typescript
// BAD
async process(): Promise<{ count: number; failed: number }> { ... }

// GOOD
interface ProcessResult {
   count: number;
   failed: number;
}
async process(): Promise<ProcessResult> { ... }
```

## Feature Endpoint DTOs (Request/Response Objects)

If the named type is a request or response body for a feature endpoint (`features/user/` or `features/admin/`), it belongs in the XML as a `<feature>` `<entity>` block — not as a hand-written interface.

```xml
<!-- CORRECT: define it in stencil-entities.xml -->
<feature name="profile" area="user" native="true">
  <entity name="NameRequest">
    <field type="string">display_name</field>
  </entity>
  <mutation name="nameUpdate" route="v1/profile/name" request="params" requestType="NameRequest" itemResult="Account.Self" />
</feature>
```

The generator will produce the typed interface and `Sanitize.for()` registry class. The controller imports and uses the generated types:

```typescript
// CORRECT: use generated types from XML
import { INameRequest, NameRequest } from './models/namerequest';
@Body(Sanitize.for(NameRequest)) input: INameRequest
```

Hand-writing a DTO interface for a feature endpoint bypasses the sanitization registry and breaks the code generation contract. If the shape needs to change, update the XML and regenerate.
